{{about|the Bangladeshi writer and academic|[[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] author, who wrote [[Akbarnama]]|Abu'l-Fazl ibn Mubarak}}
{{Infobox officeholder | name = Abul Fazal | office=[[Vice-chancellor]] of [[University of Chittagong]] | term_start = 9 April 1973 | term_end = 27 November 1975 | predecessor = [[M Innas Ali]] | successor = [[Abdul Karim (historian)|Abdul Karim]] | birth_date = {{birth date|1903|7|1|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Satkania Upazila|Satkania]], [[Chittagong District|Chittagong]], [[Bengal Presidency]], [[British India]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1983|5|4|1903|7|1|df=y}} | death_place = Chittagong, Bangladesh | occupation = educationist, writer | nationality = Bangladeshi | alma_mater = {{unbulleted list|[[University of Dhaka]]|[[Calcutta University]]}} | education = MS (Bengali Literature) | awards = [[#Awards|full list]] | children = [[Abul Momen]] }}
'''Abul Fazal''' (1 July 1903 – 4 May 1983)<ref name=bpedia>{{cite book |last=Banu |first=Sayeda |year=2012 |chapter=Fazal, Abul |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Fazal,_Abul |editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A. |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]}}</ref> was a [[Bangladesh]]i writer and academic.<ref name=dstar>{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/beta2/news/abul-fazals-30th-death-anniversary-observed/|title=Abul Fazal's 30th death anniversary observed|date=2013-05-07|accessdate=2013-05-07|publisher=The Daily Star}}</ref> He served as the 4th [[vice-chancellor]] of [[University of Chittagong]].<ref name=vc>{{cite web | url=http://www.cu.ac.bd/ctguni/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=49:vc-pro-vc-list&catid=38:chancellors&Itemid=61 | title=Vice-Chancellors | publisher=University of Chittagong | accessdate=7 July 2016}}</ref> He was awarded [[Bangla Academy Literary Award]] in 1962 and [[Independence Day Award]] in 2012 (posthumously).<ref name=bpedia/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-227731|title=PM distributes Independence Award 2012|date=2012-03-26|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-12-03|language=en}}</ref>
==Early life and education== Fazal was born in [[Chittagong District]] in 1903 to Moulvi Fazlur Rahman, an [[Imam]] of Chittagong Jame Masjid.<ref name=bpedia/> Fazal earned [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] from the [[University of Dhaka]].<ref name=bpedia/> He passed [[Master of Arts|M.A.]] in Bengali language and literature from [[Calcutta University]] in 1940.<ref name=bpedia/>
== Career == Fazal began his career as an Imam. He taught in multiple schools as a teacher. In 1941, he became a professor of Krishnanagar College and later of [[Chittagong College]]. He served as the [[vice-chancellor]] of the [[University of Chittagong]] from 1973 to 1975.<ref name=vc/>
Fazal served as a member in charge of education and culture of the advisory council of the Government of Bangladesh during 1975–23 June 1977.<ref name=bpedia/>
==Works== Fazal wrote in a variety of genres: novels, short stories, plays, memoirs, travels etc. He also wrote about religion. Some of his writings include Matir Prthibi (1940), Bichitra Katha (1940), Rekhachitra (1966) and Durdiner Dinlipi (1972).
===Novels=== * ''Chouchir'' (''Splintered'', 1934) * ''Prodip O Patongo'' (''Torch and Insects'', 1940) * ''Ranga Probhat'' (''The Crimson Dawn'', 1957) * ''Khuda O Asha'' (''Hunger and Hope'', 1964).
==Awards== * [[Bangla Academy Literary Award]] (1962) * President's National Award (1966)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.priyo.com/entertainment/2012/05/05/abul-fazals-29th-death-anniver-50797.html |title=Abul Fazal's 29th death anniversary|publisher=Priyo News|date=2012-05-05|accessdate=2013-05-06}}</ref> * The Adamjee Literary Award (1966) * Honorary Doctorate from the University of Dhaka (1974) * The Nasiruddin Gold Medal (1980) * The Muktadhara Literary Award (1981) * The Abdul Hai Literary Award (1982) * [[Independence Day Award]] (2012)
