{{Infobox language |name=Anuak |states=[[Ethiopia]], [[South Sudan]] |region=[[Gambela Region]], [[Upper Nile State]] |ethnicity=[[Anuak people]] |speakers=140,000 |date = 1991–2007 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Nilo-Saharan |fam2=[[Eastern Sudanic languages|Eastern Sudanic]] |fam3=[[Nilotic languages|Nilotic]] |fam4=[[Western Nilotic]] |fam5=[[Luo languages|Luo]] |fam6=Northern |fam7=Jur |iso3=anu |glotto=anua1242 |glottorefname=Anuak }}
'''Anuak''' or '''Anywa''' is a [[Nilotic languages|Nilotic]] language of the [[Nilo-Saharan languages|Nilo-Saharan language family]]. It is spoken primarily in the Western part of [[Ethiopia]] by the [[Anuak people|Anuak]]. Other names for this language include: ''Anyuak, Anywa, Yambo, Jambo, Yembo, Bar, Burjin, Miroy, Moojanga, Nuro''.<ref>Raymond G. Gordon Jr., ed. 2005. ''Ethnologue: Languages of the World''. 15th edition. Dallas: Summer Institute of Linguistics.</ref> Anuak, Päri, and Jur-Luwo comprise a dialect cluster.<ref>Reh, Mechthild (1996): Anywa Language: Description and Internal Reconstructions. Köln: Rüdiger Köppe. p.5</ref> The most thorough description of the Anuak language is Reh (1996) ''Anywa Language: Description and Internal Reconstructions'', which also includes glossed texts.
Anywa does not have [[Fricative_consonant|phonemic fricatives]].
