'''Cypriot Greek''' ({{lang-el|Κυπριακά}}) is the [[Variety (linguistics)|variety]] of [[Modern Greek]] that is spoken by the majority of the [[Cyprus|Cypriot]] populace and [[Greek Cypriot diaspora]]. It is a markedly divergent variety as it differs from [[Standard Modern Greek]]{{efn|group=note|Standard Modern Greek is the variety based on [[Demotic Greek|Demotic]] (but with elements of [[Katharevousa]]) that became the official language of [[Greece]] in 1976. See also: [[Greek language question]].}} in various aspects of its [[lexicon]],{{sfn|Ammon|2006|p=1886}} [[phonetics]], [[phonology]], [[Morphology (linguistics)|morphology]], [[syntax]] and even [[pragmatics]],{{sfn|Themistocleous|Katsoyannou|Armosti|Christodoulou|2012|p=262}} not only for historical reasons, but also because of geographical isolation, different settlement patterns, and extensive contact with [[Linguistic typology|typologically distinct]] languages.{{sfn|Ammon|2006|pp=1886–1887}}

==Classification==
 [[File:Griechisch Isoglossen 1900.png|thumb|300px|Some phonological phenomena Cypriot shares with varieties of the Aegean: word-initial gemination; word-final {{IPA|/n/}}; and palatalisation of {{IPA|/k/}} to {{IPA|[t͡ʃ]}}.]]
Cypriot Greek is not an evolution of ancient [[Arcadocypriot Greek]], but derives from Byzantine [[Medieval Greek]].{{sfn|Joseph|Tserdanelis|2003|p=823}} It has traditionally been placed in the [[Varieties of Modern Greek#Core dialects|southeastern group of Modern Greek varieties]], along with the dialects of the [[Dodecanese]] and [[Chios]] (with which it shares several phonological phenomena).

Though Cypriot Greek tends to be regarded as a [[Dialect#"Dialect" or "language"|dialect]] by its speakers, it is unintelligible to speakers of Standard Modern Greek without adequate prior exposure.{{sfn|Arvaniti|2006|p=26}} Greek-speaking Cypriots are [[diglossia|diglossic]] in the [[vernacular]] Cypriot Greek (the "low" variety) and Standard Modern Greek (the "high" variety).{{sfn|Arvaniti|2006|p=25}}{{sfn|Tsiplakou|2012}} Cypriot Greek is itself a [[dialect continuum]] with an emerging [[wikt:koine|koine]].{{sfn|Arvaniti|2006|pp=26–27}} {{harvtxt|Davy|Ioannou|Panayotou|1996}} argue that diglossia has given way to a "post-diglossic [dialectal] continuum [...] a quasi-continuous spread of overlapping varieties".{{sfn|Davy|Ioannou|Panayotou|1996|pp=131,135}}

==Phonology==
Studies of the phonology of Cypriot Greek are few and tend to examine very specific phenomena, e.g. [[gemination]], "glide hardening". A general overview of the phonology of Cypriot Greek has only ever been attempted once, by {{harvnb|Newton|1972}}, but parts of it are now contested.

===Consonants===
Cypriot Greek has geminate and [[palato-alveolar consonant]]s, which Standard Modern Greek lacks, as well as a contrast between {{IPA|[ɾ]}} and {{IPA|[r]}}, which Standard Modern Greek also lacks.{{sfn|Arvaniti|2010|pp=3–4}} The table below, adapted from {{harvnb|Arvaniti|2010|p=4}}, depicts the consonantal inventory of Cypriot Greek.

