Stops {{IPA|/p t c k/}} and affricate {{IPA|/t͡ʃ/}} are [[Aspiration (phonetics)|unaspirated]] and may be pronounced weakly [[Voicing (phonetics)|voiced]] in fast speech.{{sfn|Arvaniti|1999|pp=2–3}} {{IPA|/pʰː tʰː cʰː kʰː/}} are always heavily [[Aspiration (phonetics)|aspirated]] and they are never preceded by nasals,{{sfn|Arvaniti|1999|p=2}} with the exception of some [[loanword|loans]], e.g. {{IPA|/ʃamˈpʰːu/}} "shampoo".{{sfn|Davy|Ioannou|Panayotou|1996|p=134}} {{IPA|/t͡ʃ/}} and {{IPA|/t͡ʃʰː/}} are [[laminal]] post-alveolars.{{sfn|Arvaniti|1999|p=3}} {{IPA|/t͡s/}} is pronounced similarly to {{IPA|/t͡ʃʰː/}}, in terms of closure duration and aspiration.{{sfn|Arvaniti|1999|p=3}}

Voiced fricatives {{IPA|/v ð ɣ/}} are often pronounced as [[Approximant consonant|approximants]] and they are regularly [[Elision|elided]] when [[Intervocalic consonant|intervocalic]].{{sfn|Arvaniti|1999|pp=2–3}} {{IPA|/ʝ/}} is similarly often realised as an approximant {{IPA link|j|[}} in weak positions.{{sfn|Arvaniti|2010|p=11}}

The palatal lateral approximant {{IPA|/ʎ/}} is most often realised as a singleton or geminate lateral {{IPA|[ʎ(ː)]}} or a singleton or geminate fricative {{IPA|[ʝ(ː)]}}, and sometimes as a glide {{IPA|[j]}} (cf. [[yeísmo]]).{{sfn|Pappas|2009|p=307}} The circumstances under which all the different variants surface are not very well understood, but {{IPA|[ʝ(ː)]}} appear to be favoured in stressed syllables and word-finally, and before {{IPA|/a e/}}.{{sfn|Pappas|2009|p=309}} {{harvnb|Pappas|2009}} identifies the following phonological and non-phonological influencing factors: stress, preceding vowel, following vowel, position inside word; and sex, education, region, and time spent living in Greece (where {{IPA|[ʎ]}} is standard).{{sfn|Pappas|2009|p=309}} {{harvnb|Arvaniti|2010}} notes that speakers of some local varieties, notably that of [[Larnaca]], "substitute" the geminate fricative for {{IPA|/ʎ/}},{{sfn|Arvaniti|2010|pp=10–11}} but {{harvnb|Pappas|2009}} contests this, saying that, "{{IPA|[ʝ(ː)]}} is robustly present in the three urban areas of Lefkosia, Lemesos and Larnaka as well as the rural Kokinohoria region, especially among teenaged speakers ... the innovative pronunciation {{IPA|[ʝ(ː)]}} is not a feature of any local [[patois]], but rather a supra-local feature."{{sfn|Pappas|2009|p=313}}

The palatal nasal {{IPA|/ɲ/}} is produced somewhat longer than other singleton nasals, though not as long as geminates. {{IPA|/z/}} is similarly "rather long".{{sfn|Arvaniti|1999|pp=2–3}}

The alveolar trill {{IPA|/r/}} is the geminate counterpart of the tap {{IPA|/ɾ/}}.{{sfn|Arvaniti|1999|p=3}}<!-- {{IPA|/ɾ/}} is devoiced before voiceless consonants.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}}-->

====Palatalisation and glide hardening====
In analyses that posit a phonemic (but not phonetic) [[glide (linguistics)|glide]] {{IPA|/j/}}, palatals and postalveolars arise from <tt>CJV</tt> (consonant–glide–vowel) clusters, namely:{{sfn|Nevins|Chirotan|2008|pp=13–14}}

{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|
* {{IPA|/mj}}<tt>V</tt>{{IPA|/}} → {{IPA|[mɲ}}<tt>V</tt>{{IPA|]}}
* {{IPA|/nj}}<tt>V</tt>{{IPA|/}} → {{IPA|[ɲː}}<tt>V</tt>{{IPA|]}}
* {{IPA|/lj}}<tt>V</tt>{{IPA|/}} → {{IPA|[ʎː}}<tt>V</tt>{{IPA|]}} or {{IPA|[ʝː}}<tt>V</tt>{{IPA|]}}
* {{IPA|/kj}}<tt>V</tt>{{IPA|/}} → {{IPA|[t͡ʃ}}<tt>V</tt>{{IPA|]}} or {{IPA|[c}}<tt>V</tt>{{IPA|]}}
* {{IPA|/xj}}<tt>V</tt>{{IPA|/}} → {{IPA|[ʃ}}<tt>V</tt>{{IPA|]}} or {{IPA|[ç}}<tt>V</tt>{{IPA|]}}
* {{IPA|/ɣj}}<tt>V</tt>{{IPA|/}} → {{IPA|[ʝ}}<tt>V</tt>{{IPA|]}}
* {{IPA|/zj}}<tt>V</tt>{{IPA|/}} → {{IPA|[ʒː}}<tt>V</tt>{{IPA|]}}
* {{IPA|/t͡sj}}<tt>V</tt>{{IPA|/}} → {{IPA|[t͡ʃʰː}}<tt>V</tt>{{IPA|]}}
}}

The glide is not assimilated, but hardens to an [[obstruent]] {{IPA|[c]}} after {{IPA|/p t f v θ ð/}} and to {{IPA|[k]}} after {{IPA|/ɾ/}}.{{sfn|Nevins|Chirotan|2008|pp=13–14}} At any rate, velar stops and fricatives are in [[complementary distribution]] with palatals and postalveolars before front vowels {{IPA|/e i/}};{{sfn|Arvaniti|1999|p=3}} that is to say, broadly, {{IPA|/k kʰː/}} are [[Palatalization (sound change)|palatalised]] to either {{IPA|[c cʰː]}} or {{IPA|[t͡ʃ t͡ʃʰː]}}; {{IPA|/x xː/}} to {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ç}} çː]}} or {{IPA|[ʃ ʃː]}}; and {{IPA|/ɣ/}} to {{IPA|[ʝ]}}.

====Geminates====
There is considerable disagreement on how to classify Cypriot Greek geminates, though they are now generally understood to be "geminates proper" (rather than clusters of identical phonemes or "[[Fortis and lenis|fortis]]" consonants).{{sfn|Arvaniti|2010|p=12}} Geminates are 1.5 to 2 times longer than singletons, depending, primarily, on position and stress.{{sfn|Arvaniti|2010|pp=4–5}} Geminates occur both word-initially and word-medially. Word-initial geminates tend to be somewhat longer.{{sfn|Arvaniti|2010|p=5}} {{harvnb|Tserdanelis|Arvaniti|2001}} have found that "for stops, in particular, this lengthening affects both closure duration and [[Voice onset time|VOT]]",{{sfn|Tserdanelis|Arvaniti|2001|p=35}} but {{harvnb|Davy|Panayotou|2003}} claim that stops contrast only in aspiration, and not duration.{{sfn|Davy|Panayotou|2003|p=8|ps=: "... there is no evidence for the assumption that CG {{IPA|/pʰ/}} is distinctively long (or geminate). The CGasp system contains simply tense aspirated and lax unaspirated stops."}} {{harvnb|Armosti|2010}} undertook a perceptual study with thirty native speakers of Cypriot Greek,{{sfn|Armosti|2010|pp=37}} and has found that both closure duration and (the duration and properties of) aspiration provide important cues in distinguishing between the two kinds of stops, but aspiration is slightly more significant.{{sfn|Armosti|2010|pp=52–53}}

====Assimilatory processes====
Word-final {{IPA|/n/}} [[Assimilation (linguistics)|assimilates]] with succeeding consonants—other than stops and affricates—at word boundaries producing post-lexical geminates.{{sfn|Arvaniti|2010|p=8}} Consequently, geminate voiced fricatives, though generally not phonemic, do occur as allophones. <!--For {{IPA|/l/}} and {{IPA|/lː/}}, this process was found to give rise to a four-way durational distinction: lexical singleton {{IPA|/l/}}, lexical geminate {{IPA|/lː/}}, {{IPA|/n/}} + singleton {{IPA|/l/}} → post-lexical {{IPA|[lˑ]}} (shorter than the lexical geminate), and {{IPA|/n/}} + geminate {{IPA|/lː/}} → post-lexical "super-geminate" {{IPA|[lːˑ]}} (longer).{{sfn|Payne|Eftychiou|2006|p=195}} This might hold true for consonants other than {{IPA|/l/}} and {{IPA|/lː/}}, but no studies have been conducted to prove that that is the case. {{harvnb|Armosti|2007}} casts doubt on whether this difference is phonemic.{{sfn|Armosti|2007|pp=763–764|ps=: "The only robust contrast was arguably between S and WI-G, i.e. between lexical categories. The post-lexical categories, and especially WB-G, were not readily identified by the subjects. No concrete evidence was found for the four categories being, in fact, four linguistically functional categories."}}--> Below are some examples of geminates to arise from [[sandhi]].
* {{IPA|/ton ˈluka/}} → {{IPA|[to‿ˈlˑuka]}} {{lang|el|τον Λούκα}} "Lucas" (acc.)
* {{IPA|/en ˈða/}} → {{IPA|[e‿ˈðːa]}} {{lang|el|εν δα}} "[he] is here"
* {{IPA|/pu tin ˈɾiza/}} → {{IPA|[pu ti‿ˈriza]}} {{lang|el|που την ρίζα}} "from the root"

In contrast, singleton stops and affricates do not undergo gemination, but become fully voiced when preceded by a nasal, with the nasal becoming [[Homorganic consonants|homorganic]].{{sfn|Arvaniti|1999|pp=2–3}} This process is not restricted to terminal nasals; singleton stops and affricates always become voiced following a nasal.{{sfn|Arvaniti|1999|p=4}}
* {{IPA|/kaˈpnizumen ˈpuɾa/}} → {{IPA|[kaˈpnizumem‿ˈbuɾa]}} {{lang|el|καπνίζουμεν πούρα}} "[we] smoke cigars"
* {{IPA|/an ˈt͡ʃe/}} → {{IPA|[an‿ˈd͡ʒe]}} {{lang|el|αν τζ̌αι}} "even though"
* {{IPA|/tin ciɾi.aˈci/}} → {{IPA|[tiɲ‿ɟirĭ.aˈci]}} {{lang|el|την Κυριακή}} "on Sunday"

Word-final {{IPA|/n/}} is altogether [[Elision|elided]] before geminate stops and consonant clusters:{{sfn|Arvaniti|1999|p=5}}
* {{IPA|/eˈpiasamen ˈfcoɾa/}} → {{IPA|[eˈpcasame‿ˈfcoɾa]}} {{lang|el|επιάσαμεν φκιόρα}} "[we] bought flowers"
* {{IPA|/ˈpa‿stin cʰːeˈlːe/}} → {{IPA|[ˈpa‿sti‿cʰːeˈlːe]}} {{lang|el|πα' στην κκελλέ}} "on the head"

Like with {{IPA|/n/}}, word-final {{IPA|/s/}} assimilates to following {{IPA|[s]}} and {{IPA|[ʃ]}} producing geminates:{{sfn|Armosti|2011|p=97}}
* {{IPA|/as ʃoˈnisi/}} → {{IPA|[a‿ʃːoˈnisi]}} {{lang|el|ας σ̌ονίσει}} "let it snow"

Lastly, word-final {{IPA|/s/}} becomes voiced when followed by a voiced consonant belonging to the same phrase:{{sfn|Arvaniti|1999|p=5}}
* {{IPA|/tis ˈmaltas/}} → {{IPA|[tiz‿ˈmaltas]}} {{lang|el|της Μάλτας}} "of [[Malta]]"
* {{IPA|/aˈɣonas ˈðromu/}} → {{IPA|[aˈɣonaz‿ˈðromu]}} {{lang|el|αγώνας δρόμου}} "race"

===Vowels===
[[File:Cypriot Greek vowel chart.svg|thumb|250px|The [[Vowel diagram|vowels]] of Cypriot Greek. Adapted from {{harvnb|Arvaniti|1999|p=4}}.]]

Cypriot Greek has a five-vowel system {{IPA|/{{IPA link|i}}, {{IPA link|u}}, {{IPA link|e̞|e}}, {{IPA link|o̞|o}}, {{IPA link|ɐ|a}}/}}{{sfn|Georgiou|2018|p=70}} that is nearly identical to that of Standard Modern Greek (see for an acoustic comparison of the two vowel systems {{harvnb|Themistocleous|2017}} and {{harvnb|Themistocleous|2017}}).

Back vowels {{IPA|/i u/}} following {{IPA|/t/}} at the end of an utterance are regularly reduced (50% of all cases presented in study) to "fricated vowels" (40% of all cases, cf. Slavic [[yer]]s), and are sometimes [[Elision|elided]] altogether (5% of all cases).{{sfn|Eftychiou|2007|p=518}}

In glide-less analyses, {{IPA|/i/}} may alternate with {{IPA|[k]}} or {{IPA|[c]}},{{sfn|Arvaniti|2010|p=1}} e.g. {{IPA|[kluvi]}} "cage" → {{IPA|[klufca]}} "cages", or {{IPA|[kulːuɾi]}} "[[wikt:koulouri|koulouri]]" → {{IPA|[kulːuɾ̥ka]}} "koulouria"; and, like in Standard Modern Greek, it is pronounced {{IPA|[ɲ]}} when found between {{IPA|/m/}} and another vowel that belongs to the same syllable,{{sfn|Arvaniti|1999|p=4}} e.g. {{IPA|[mɲa]}} "one" (f.).

===Stress===
Cypriot Greek has [[Stress (linguistics)|"dynamic" stress]].{{sfn|Arvaniti|1999|p=5}} Both consonants and vowels are longer in stressed than in unstressed syllables, and the effect is stronger word-initially.{{sfn|Arvaniti|2010|pp=17–18}} There is only one stress per word, and it can fall on any of the last four syllables. Stress on the fourth syllable from the end of a word is rare and normally limited to certain verb forms. Because of this possibility, however, when words with antepenultimate stress are followed by an enclitic in Cypriot Greek, no extra stress is added (unlike Standard Modern Greek, where the stress can only fall on one of the last three syllables),{{sfn|Arvaniti|1999|p=5}} e.g. Cypriot Greek {{lang|el|το ποδήλατον μου}} {{IPA|[to poˈðilato‿mːu]}}, Standard Modern Greek {{lang|el|το ποδήλατό μου}} {{IPA|[to poˌðilaˈto‿mu]}} "my bicycle".

==Grammar==
{{Further|Modern Greek grammar}}

An overview of syntactic and morphological differences between Standard Modern Greek and Cypriot Greek can be found in {{harvnb|Hadjioannou|Tsiplakou|Kappler|2011|pp=568-9}}.
<!--

===Morphology===
The main morphological differences between Standard Modern Greek and Cypriot Greek are the following:{{sfn|Hadjioannou|Tsiplakou|Kappler|2011|p=568}}
* different [[interrogative word]] for "what" {{lang|el|ίντα}} {{IPA|[ˈi<sup>n</sup>da]}} instead of {{lang|el|τί}} {{IPA|[ti]}}
* different [[determiner]] {{lang|el|τες}} {{IPA|[tes]}} instead of {{lang|el|τις}} {{IPA|[tis]}} in the [[grammatical gender|feminine]] [[accusative case|accusative]] plural
* penultimate stress in the [[nominative case|nominative]] plural of second [[declension]] nouns and the [[genitive case|genitive]] plural of first declension feminine [[pronoun]]s{{clarify|reason=Please provide the NOM sg. place of accent of (various) cases so that a comparison can be made with SMG.|date=April 2015}}
* different plural [[morpheme]]s, e.g. {{lang|el|γιούδες}} {{IPA|[ˈʝuðes]}} instead of {{lang|el|γιοι}} {{IPA|[ʝi]}} "sons" (sg. {{lang|el|γιος}}){{clarify|reason=In which declension(s)/group(s)?|date=April 2015}}
* different [[demonstrative pronoun]] {{lang|el|τουν}} {{IPA|[tun-]}} instead of {{lang|el|τούτο}} {{IPA|[tuto]}}{{clarify|reason=Probably NEU; if so, please state it explicitly. Similarly, if instead it's MASC (ACC) or both NEU and MASC (ACC).|date=April 2015}}
* different third person plural suffix in present and past tense {{IPA|[-usin]}} and {{IPA|[-asin]}} instead of {{IPA|[-un]}} and {{IPA|[-an]}}, respectively
* different second person plural morpheme in past tenses {{IPA|[-mete]}} instead of {{IPA|[-nate]}}{{clarify|reason=SMG [-nate]? In SMG, [-nate] means that the verb's root ends in n (the suffix is [-ate]). Does this mean that SMG 'lynate' is 'lymete' in CG changing the root? Or is this simply a typo and [-ate] (or [-gate] or [-sate]) was meant? Or is it a case of 'kano' vs 'kam(n)o'? In any case, what is the meaning of 'morpheme' in this context?|date=April 2015}} 
* syllabic [[augment (linguistics)|augment]] {{IPA|[e]}} in past tenses{{clarify|reason=Does this mean that it's universally applied? Cause SMG verbs also get syllabic augments, they just don't get them consistently or at all persons, or put in another way, consistency is found only when the augment is accented in non compound forms of the verbs.|date=April 2015}}
* different future particle {{lang|el|εννά}} {{IPA|[eˈnːa]}} instead of {{lang|el|θα}} {{IPA|[θa]}}
* different negation marker in non-indicative [[grammatical mood|mood]] {{lang|el|μεν}} {{IPA|[men]}} instead of {{lang|el|μη(ν)}} {{IPA|[mi(n)]}}

===Syntax===
The main syntactic differences between Standard Modern Greek and Cypriot Greek are the following:{{sfn|Hadjioannou|Tsiplakou|Kappler|2011|p=569}}
* [[clitic]] comes after the verb instead of before it when the verb is emphasized and in the beginning of the sentence, e.g. {{lang|el|είδες το}} {{IPA|[ˈiðes to]}} instead of {{lang|el|το είδες}} {{IPA|[to ˈiðes]}} "you saw it"
* obligatory [[cleft sentence|clefting]] in wh-questions induced by ''inda'', e.g. {{IPA|[ˈi<sup>n</sup>da <sup>m</sup>bu ˈiðes]}} "what is it that you saw?" instead of {{IPA|[ti ˈiðes]}} "what did you see?"
* optional clefting in other wh-questions
* focus clefting (no focus movement), e.g. {{IPA|[e ˈ<sup>n</sup>di ˈkseɲːa <sup>m</sup>bu ˈiðes]}} "it is Xenia that you saw" for {{IPA|[tin ˈkseɲa ˈiðes]}} "you saw Xenia"
* indirect before direct object with post-verbal clitics, e.g. {{IPA|[ˈstil mu to]}} "send me it" instead of {{IPA|[ˈstile ˈto mu]}} "send it to me"
-->

==Vocabulary==
More loanwords are in everyday use than in Standard Modern Greek.{{sfn|Ammon|2006|p=1886}} These come from [[Old French]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Occitan language|Provençal]], [[Turkish language|Turkish]] and, increasingly, from [[English language|English]]. There are also Arabic expressions like {{lang|el|μάσ̌σ̌αλλα}} {{IPA|[ˈmaʃːalːa]}} "[[mashallah]]" and {{lang|el|ίσ̌σ̌αλλα}} {{IPA|[ˈiʃːalːa]}} "[[inshallah]]". Much of the Cypriot core vocabulary is different to the modern standard's, e.g. {{lang|el|συντυχάννω}} {{IPA|[sindiˈxanːo]}} in addition to μιλώ "I talk", {{lang|el|θωρώ}} {{IPA|[θοˈɾo]}} instead of βλέπω "I look", etc. A historically interesting example is the occasional use of Archaic πόθεν instead of από που for the interrogative "from where?"

''[[Ethnologue]]'' reports that the [[lexical similarity]] between Cypriot Greek and [[Demotic Greek]] is in the range of 84–93%.<ref>{{e18|ell|Greek}}</ref>

==Orthography==
{{See also|Modern Greek#Writing system}}

There is no established orthography for Cypriot Greek.{{sfn|Arvaniti|1999|p=1}}{{sfn|Themistocleous|2010|p=158}} Efforts have been made to introduce [[diacritic]]s to the [[Greek alphabet]] to represent [[palato-alveolar consonant]]s found in Cypriot, but not in Standard Modern Greek, e.g. the [[caron|combining caron]] {{angle bracket|ˇ}}, by the authors of the [http://lexcy.library.ucy.ac.cy/Lexicon.aspx "Syntychies" lexicographic database] at the [[University of Cyprus]].{{sfn|Themistocleous|Katsoyannou|Armosti|Christodoulou|2012|pp=263–264}} When diacritics are not used, an epenthetic {{angle bracket|ι}}—often accompanied by the systematic substitution of the preceding consonant letter—may be used to the same effect (as in [[Polish language|Polish]]), e.g. Standard Modern Greek {{lang|el|παντζάρι}} {{IPA|[paˈ(n)d͡zaɾi]}} → Cypriot Greek {{lang|el|ππαντζ'''ι'''άρι}} {{IPA|[pʰːaˈnd͡ʒaɾi]}}, Standard Modern Greek {{lang|el|χέρι}} {{IPA|[ˈçeɾi]}} → Cypriot Greek {{lang|el|'''σι'''έρι}} {{IPA|[ˈʃeɾi]}}.

[[Geminate]]s (and [[Aspirated consonant|aspirates]]) are represented by two of the same letter, e.g. {{lang|el|σή'''μμ'''ερα}} {{IPA|[ˈsimːeɾa]}} "today", though this may not be done in cases where the spelling would not coincide with Standard Modern Greek's, e.g. {{lang|el|σήμμερα}} would still be spelt {{lang|el|σήμερα}}.{{efn|group=note|Geminates are present in Cypriot Greek and were present (and distinct) in Ancient and earlier Koine, but they are not in Standard Modern Greek. Late twentieth century spelling reforms in Greece were not indiscriminate, i.e. some words are still spelt with two consecutive consonant letters, but are not pronounced that way. In addition, Cypriot Greek has developed geminates in words where they were not previously found.}}

In [[computer-mediated communication]], Cypriot Greek, like Standard Modern Greek, is commonly written in the [[Latin script]],{{sfn|Themistocleous|2010|pp=158–159}} and English spelling conventions may be adopted for shared sounds,{{sfn|Themistocleous|2010|p=165}} e.g. {{angle bracket|sh}} for {{IPA|/ʃ/}} (and {{IPA|/ʃː/}}).

==History==
{{Unreferenced section|date=February 2013}}

Cyprus was cut off from the rest of the Greek-speaking world from the 7th to the 10th century <small>AD</small> due to Arab attacks. It was reintegrated in the [[Byzantine Empire]] in 962 to be isolated again in 1191 when it fell to the hands of the [[Third Crusade|Crusaders]]. These periods of isolation led to the development of various linguistic characteristics distinct from [[Byzantine Greek]].

The oldest surviving written works in Cypriot date back to the [[Medieval period]]. Some of these are: the legal code of the [[Kingdom of Cyprus]], the [[Assizes of Jerusalem]]; the chronicles of [[Leontios Machairas]] and Georgios Voustronios; and a collection of sonnets in the manner of [[Francesco Petrarca]]. In the past hundred years, the dialect has been used in poetry (with major poets being [[Vasilis Michaelides]] and [[Dimitris Lipertis]]). It is also traditionally used in folk songs and {{lang|el|τσιαττιστά}} (battle poetry, a form of playing [[the Dozens]]) and the tradition of {{lang|el|ποιητάρηες}} (bards).

In the late seventies, Minister of Education [[Chrysostomos A. Sofianos]] upgraded the status of Cypriot by introducing it in education. More recently, it has been used in [[Music of Cyprus|music]], e.g. in reggae by Hadji Mike and in rap by several Cypriot hip hop groups, such as Dimiourgoi Neas Antilipsis (DNA). Locally produced television shows, usually comedies or soap operas, make use of the dialect, e.g. "Vourate Geitonoi" ({{lang|el|βουράτε}} instead of {{lang|el|τρέξτε}}) or "Oi Takkoi" ({{lang|el|Τάκκος}} being a uniquely Cypriot name). The 2006 feature film ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Man's Chest]]'' features actor Jimmy Roussounis arguing in Cypriot with another crew member speaking [[Gibrizlidja]] (Cypriot Turkish) about a captain's hat they find in the sea. [[Peter Polycarpou]] routinely spoke in Cypriot in his role as Chris Theodopolopoudos in the British television comedy series ''[[Birds of a Feather]]''. In Episode 04 Season 01 of American TV series ''[[The Leftovers (TV series)|The Leftovers]]'' which aired on 20 July 2014, Alex Malaos's character uses the dialect saying ''"Εκατάλαβα σε".''

Today, Cypriot Greek is the only variety of Modern Greek with a significant presence of spontaneous use online, including [[blog]]s and [[internet forum]]s, and there exists a variant of [[Greeklish]] that reflects its distinct [[phonology]].

