{{EngvarB|date=January 2018}} {{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}} {{Infobox philosopher |image = Professor Maria Baghramian, UCD School of Philosophy.jpg |caption = Professor Maria Baghramian, UCD School of Philosophy |region = [[Western Philosophy]] |era = [[20th-century philosophy]] |name = Maria Baghramian |birth_date = |birth_place = [[Tehran]], Iran |school_tradition = [[Analytic philosophy]] |main_interests = [[Philosophy of language]], [[relativism]], American 20th century philosophy }}
'''Maria Baghramian''' is a professor of philosophy at the [[University College Dublin]] (UCD).<ref name="Academic profile at UCD School of Philosophy">[http://www.ucd.ie/philosophy/staff/mariabaghramian/ Academic profile at UCD School of Philosophy]</ref> Her main research areas are [[philosophy of language]], [[relativism]] and [[rationality]], 20th-century American Philosophy ([[Hilary Putnam|Putnam]], [[Donald Davidson (philosopher)|Davidson]], [[Rorty]], [[Willard Van Orman Quine|Quine]]), [[pragmatism]], [[philosophy of mind]], and [[cognitive science]]. Her research and publications primarily focus on discussions of objectivity, relativism and [[pluralism (disambiguation)|pluralism]] as solutions to the intractable diversity of beliefs and values, and on contemporary American Philosophy, particularly as it relates to the work of Quine, Davidson, Putnam and Rorty. She was elected a member of the [[Royal Irish Academy]] in 2010.<ref>[http://www.ria.ie/About/Membership/Member-List.aspx Royal Irish Academy members] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130101021939/http://www.ria.ie/about/Membership/Member-List.aspx |date=1 January 2013 }}</ref> Since 2003 she has been the Chief Editor of the [[International Journal of Philosophical Studies]] (IJPS).<ref>[http://www.tandfonline.com/action/aboutThisJournal?show=editorialBoard&journalCode=riph20 International Journal of Philosophical Studies, IJPS]</ref>
Baghramian graduated from [[Queen's University Belfast]] in Philosophy and Social Anthropology (1983) with a Double First.<ref>[http://www.ucd.ie/philosophy/staff/mariabaghramian/rms/ Baghramian UCD Research Portal Page]</ref> She received a PhD from [[Trinity College Dublin]] (TCD) in [[Philosophy of Logic]] under the supervision of [[Timothy Williamson]] (1990). Baghramian has taught in TCD and since 1991 in UCD. She is the Head of the School of Philosophy (2011–2013) and a co-director of the Post Graduate Programme in Cognitive Science at UCD (since 2000).<ref>[http://cogsci.ucd.ie/contact.php UCD Cognitive Science webpage]</ref>
Baghramian is the founder and the president of the Society for Women in Philosophy (SWIP) – Ireland<ref>[http://www.swip-ireland.com/ Society for Women in Philosophy (SWIP) – Ireland]</ref> (2010) and of Aporo: Irish Network of Philosophical Research.<ref>[http://www.aporo.org/ APORO]</ref> She is an adviser to China Association of Philosophy of Language<ref>[http://wenku.baidu.com/view/012573292af90242a895e535.html Philosophy of Language in China]</ref> and Chairperson of the panel of Philosophy and Theology at [[The Undergraduate Awards]].<ref>[http://www.undergraduateawards.com/2012_Judges.asp The Undergraduate Awards]</ref> She has organised the Joint Session of the [[Aristotelian Society]] and [[Mind Association]] conferences in 1996 and 2010.<ref>[http://ucdjointsession2010.com UCD Joint Session]</ref> She is the principal investigator of a research project on the American Voice in Philosophy<ref>[http://www.american-voice.org/ American Voice in Philosophy]</ref> with the Irish Research Council.<ref>[http://www.research.ie/ Irish Research Council]</ref> In the academic year 2013–14, she was a visiting Philosophy Fellow and Fulbright Scholar at the Department of Philosophy, [[Harvard]] (February–July 2014), a visiting Scholar at [[Institut Jean Nicod]], [[École normale supérieure]], in Paris (Autumn 2013), a lecturer at the 2013 Autumn School in Yerevan State University<ref>[http://www.ysu.am/news/en/1382008212 Analytical philosophy Autumn school YSU]</ref> and at the 2014 Oxford/Yale Summer School in Philosophy in China.
Maria Baghramian was born in [[Tehran]], [[Iran]] in an [[Armenians|Armenian]] family and is married to the composer/musicologist [[Hormoz Farhat]].
== Selected works ==
* (Ed.) (2014) The Many Faces of Relativism. London/New York: Taylor and Francis. * (Ed.) (2013) ''Donald Davidson: Life and Words''. London/NewYork: Routledge. * (Ed.) (2012) ''Reading Putnam''. London/New York: Routledge. * (2004) ''Relativism: The Problems of Philosophy Series''. London/New York: Routledge. * (Ed.) (2000) with Atracta Ingram. ''Pluralism: The Philosophy and Politics of Diversity''. London/New York: Routledge.<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00IN3LY1A/ref=rdr_kindle_ext_tmb The Kindle edition of the pluralism]</ref> Translated into Chinese.<ref>[http://www.books.com.tw/exep/prod/china/chinafile.php?item=CN10698391 Chinese translation of Pluralism]</ref> * (1999) ''Modern Philosophy of Language''. London: J.M. Dent 1998 and Washington:Counterpoint 1999.
